  "text": "Deep learning-based channel decoding is doomed by the curse of dimensionality [CITATION_1] : for a short code of length N = 100 and rate r = 0.5, 2 50 different codewords exist, which are far too many to fully train any neural network (NN) in practice. The only way that a NN can be trained for practical blocklengths is, if it learns some form of decoding algorithm which can infer the full codebook from training on a small fraction of codewords. However, to be able to learn a decoding algorithm, the code itself must have some structure which is based on a simple encoding rule, like in the case of convolutional or algebraic codes. The goal of this paper is to shed some light on the question whether structured codes are easier to \"learn\" than random codes, and whether a NN can decode codewords that it has never seen during training.",
